Data Science Challenge: Card Transactions¶

This Notebook aims to analyze the credit card fraud based on the card transactions data. It consists of five parts:¶

(1) Data loading and a brief summary of the data strucutre

(2) Visualization of the features in the data (transactionAmount, etc.)

(3) Analyze two types of the duplicate transactions: reversal & multi-swipe

(4) An Xgboost model is built to predict the fraud and the important indicators of the fraud

(5) Caveats and Future steps

Part 1: Data Load¶

The transaction data consists of 786,363 transactions and 29 variables. The transactions is from 5,000 unique accounts and customers.

For each record, the variables include card information (CVV, credit limit, balance, etc.), transaction information (transaction time, amount, etc.), mechant information (merchant name, category, etc.).

The flag 'isFraud' indicate if the transaction is Fraud, and there is 1.58% fraud in the given data.

For categorical and boolean variables, the bar plot is used to visualize the unique value and distribution. For numerical variables, the descriptive analysis is conducted, as well as historgam and boxplot are used to check the distribution (Plots in Part 2).

Part 2: Visualization of Numeric Variables¶

This part plots the boxplot and histrogram of four numeric variables in the data.

In overall, the variables are right skewed distributed, and some outliers are detected from the boxplot

Summary of numerical variable distribution¶

  • Credit Limit:

    Based on the histogram, the variable is more like a discrete variable, and the distribution shows multi-peaks (5,000, 15,000, 50,000). But most of the values are between 0 ~ 25,000.

  • Available money

    The histogram is right skewed. Most of the available amount is in 0 - 10,000. Also there is negative available money detected.

  • Transaction amount

    As previous two variables, the distribution is also right skewed. Most of the transactions are between 0- 500. But some large amount transaction as high as $2,000 is observed

  • Current balance

    Also right skewed distribution. In overall the value is between 0 - 10,000. There are some extreme large balance close to the highest credit limit (~50,000)

Part 3. Duplicate Transactions¶

In this section, the logic of reversal and multi-swipe transactions are programmed.

The reversal transactions are located based on the 'transactionType' equals 'REVERSAL'; the multi-swipe transactions are defined based on duplication in multiple keys (all keys exclude available money, current balance, and transaction time but keep the transaction date the same day), only the first payment is considered normal transaction, the rest of them are consider as duplicates.

  • There are 20,303 reveral transactions with total amount of $2,821,792

  • There are 7,628 multi-swipe transactions with total amount of $1,097,270.99

Both of the duplicate categories have Fraud rate of 1.7%, slightly higher than the rate in total transaction.

The distribution of categorical and numeric variables are checked and they are similar with the transaction data. So it could be a random scenario based on the given data.

Part 4 Modeling¶

This part consists of two steps:

  • Data Preprocess

    • Missing data in the categorical variables are replaced with the most frequent value
    • Dummy coded the categorical variables
    • Self-defined variable (CVV match or not)
    • Randomly split the data to train & test portions (70%:30%)

  • Modeling

    • XGBoost models is utlized, and best model obtained based on the Grid Search and F1 score is used as a criteria since it's imbalanced data
    • The performance is evaluated based on F1 score (0.097), and confusion matrix is visualized
    • Variable importance visualized based on Shap value
      • The higher the transaction amount, the higher possibility it might be fraud
      • PosEntry Mode 09 has higher chance of fraudulent transaction and PosEntry Mode 05 seems more reliable.
      • When Card not present at purchase, it is more chance to be a fraud
      • The fuel, mobile apps, health, online subscription mechant purchase has less likely to be fraud, while online purchase and airlines have higher chance of fraud

    df[var] = imp.fit_transform(df[var].values.reshape(-1,1))[:,0]

Modeling - XGBoost¶
In [41]:
# grid search 
parameters =  {'objective':['reg:logistic'],
            'max_depth': [3,4,5,6],
            'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1],
            'n_estimators': [200, 250, 300, 350],
            'alpha':[0.01, 0.1, 0.5],            
            'colsample_bytree': [0.3, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8],
            'scale_pos_weight':[30, 50, 70],           
            }

xgb_model = xgb.XGBClassifier(random_state = 42)

grid = GridSearchCV(estimator = xgb_model, param_grid = parameters, scoring = 'f1', n_jobs = -1, cv = 3) 

grid_result = grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))

Best: 0.097453 using {'alpha': 0.5, 'colsample_bytree': 0.8, 'learning_rate': 0.1, 'max_depth': 5, 'n_estimators': 250, 'objective': 'reg:logistic', 'scale_pos_weight': 30}

Part 5 Caveats and Next Steps¶

There are some efforts can be made in order to improve the model performance

  • Missing data
    • Mechant geo info are all missing in current data, see if it can be obtained through other sources
    • Other missing variables is replaced by most frequent value, further missing data analysis can be conducted to figure out better ways to fill in the missingness
  • Preprocess data
    • Binning the numeric variables to see if the performance improved
    • The current version use class weight in the Xbgoost package to handle imbalanced data, other approaches such as downsampling or SMOT to upsampling can be tried to see if there is improvement
  • More feature engineering
    • Current data: consecutive purchases, account age, transaction number and time since address change date, etc.
    • Other potential data: payment history data, geographic information, etc.
  • Try other algorithms
    • Try techniques like PCA for variable reduction, K-means, SVM, or stacking different models
    • Customize the loss function in grid search to make the model more suitable for imbalanced fraud detection data
